)

#question[
  *Image Histogram*: accumulate the number of each pixel value, then draw a histogram for each output image from previous tasks.
]

== Algorithm

For a grayscale image $f$, the histogram is the discrete count function
$
  H(k) = |{ (x, y) : f(x, y) = k }|, quad k in \{0, 1, dots, 255\}.
$
That is, $H(k)$ counts how many pixels in the image have intensity value $k$. The histogram therefore summarizes the intensity distribution of the image without using spatial position information.

== Implementation

The program accumulates the histogram by scanning all pixels once and incrementing one of 256 bins according to the grayscale value. After accumulation, the counts are rendered as a bar chart image with labeled axes, grid lines, and one bar for each intensity level from $0$ to $255$.

#figure(
  caption: [Histograms of the noisy image and the filtered outputs. (a) Histogram of the noisy input image. (b) Histogram after median filtering with the best Q1 configuration. (c) Histogram after Gaussian filtering with the best Q2 configuration. (d) Histogram after the best combined filter from Q3.],
  grid(
    columns: (1fr, 1fr),
    gutter: 10pt,
    [
      #image("project_hw2/result_imgs/CKS_noise-his.png", width: 100%)
      #text(size: 9pt)[(a) Noisy input histogram.]
    ],
    [
      #image("project_hw2/result_imgs/CKS_Q1-his.png", width: 100%)
      #text(size: 9pt)[(b) Q1 median-filter histogram.]
    ],

    [
      #image("project_hw2/result_imgs/CKS_Q2-his.png", width: 100%)
      #text(size: 9pt)[(c) Q2 Gaussian-filter histogram.]
    ],
    [
      #image("project_hw2/result_imgs/CKS_Q3-his.png", width: 100%)
      #text(size: 9pt)[(d) Q3 combined-filter histogram.]
    ],
  ),
)

Comparing Fig. 4(a)-4(d), the noisy image in Fig. 4(a) shows sharp spikes near intensities $0$ and $255$, which are clear signatures of impulse-like corruption. After median filtering in Fig. 4(b), these extreme spikes are largely removed and the histogram returns to a clearer bimodal structure, corresponding more closely to the dark and bright regions of the scene. In Fig. 4(c), Gaussian filtering smooths the histogram itself: neighboring bins vary more continuously, but the main peaks are lower because the weighted average spreads intensities across nearby values. Finally, Fig. 4(d) combines these two effects: the extreme spikes are suppressed as in Q1, while the overall distribution is smoother than in Fig. 4(b). This is consistent with the fact that Q3 achieves the best PSNR among the tested outputs.
